well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals weakness in wrist and finger extension, and decreased sensation over the posterior aspect of the forearm and hand.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves is most likely affected in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Radial nerve","Ulnar nerve","Median nerve","Musculocutaneous nerve","Axillary nerve"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E dysfunction. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadial nerve \u003C/strong\u003Efunction\u003Cstrong\u003E:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESensory innervation: dorsal aspect of the hand, dorsal aspect of the thumb, second and third finger, dorsolateral aspect of the fourth finger (sparing finger tips). \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMotor innervation: posterior arm and forearm muscles, wrist and finger extensors \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUlnar nerve\u003C/strong\u003E injury would primarily affect the intrinsic muscles of the hand and cause sensory loss over the medial aspect of the hand, the fifth finger and the medial aspect of the fourth finger. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedian nerve\u003C/strong\u003E injury would affect the anterior forearm muscles and some hand muscles, leading to difficulty with wrist flexion and thumb opposition, not wrist extension. Sensory loss would occur affect the lateral volar aspect of the hand, from the thumb to the lateral edge of the fourth finger, including the finger tips. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMusculocutaneous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E injury would affect the anterior compartment of the arm, leading to weakness in elbow flexion, not wrist extension, and sensory loss over the lateral and volar aspect of the forearm. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAxillary nerve\u003C/strong\u003E injury would affect the deltoid and teres minor muscles, leading to weakness in shoulder abduction, not wrist extension. Sensory loss would occur laterally over the shoulder. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The radial nerve has sensory and motor functions","The radial nerve provides sensory innervation to the dorsal aspect of the hand, dorsal aspect of the thumb, second and third finger and dorsolateral aspect of the fourth finger (sparing finger tips).","The radial nerve provides motor innervation to the posterior arm and forearm muscles, wrist and finger extensors"],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61688"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18113"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61688"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T10:57:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T10:58:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10827"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76184"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships"